[2] Brazil (Mato Grosso)
Date: Wed 30 Sep 2009
Source: Media News [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.midianews.com.br/?pg=noticias&cat=3&idnot=8378>


The governor [of Mato Grosso state], Blairo Maggi, met on Tuesday [29
Sep 2009], with officials from Cuiaba and Varzea Grande looking to
discuss public policies directed at combating dengue before the rainy
season. The initiative seeks partnerships aiming to avoid an epidemic
in the 2 cities and reduce the rates of cases reported in 2009, which
reached 11 031, with 307 serious cases and 8 deaths in the capital.
Already in the industrial city, 3800 [cases] have been recorded, 198
of them confirmed and 6 deaths.

At the meeting, the technical staff of the state Secretariat of Health
gave an explanation on the [vector abundance] indexes in the 2 largest
cities in the state, as well as some recommendations to control the
disease. Among these is integrated collaboration between the 2
municipalities, materials for health workers, the hiring of more
[health] agents for the areas not covered, training, and supervision
of the work.

According to governor Maggi, there will be a joint effort, in
partnership with municipalities, to clean the cities with the
expansion of waste disposal, elimination of the breeding sites that
are formed by the accumulation of trash, a joint legal action in
relation to the continuous cleaning of vacant lots; water supply, to
ensure a continuous supply and adequacy of water supplies; ensuring
adequate legislation for places where materials are stored that can
serve as a breeding sites (tires, old metal [junk] and other [trash]).

In partnership with Greater Cuiaba and Varzea Grande, the state
government will invest in advertising campaigns to raise awareness.
Strategies will be defined based on the results of qualitative
investigations.

"There is nobody at fault for the increase in cases, since it is a
public health [problem], which is the responsibility of us all. Thus,
we must work together to avoid that in 2010 numbers increase again,"
said Maggi.

The meeting included the deputy mayors of Cuiaba and Varzea Grande,
Galindo, and Zaeli Tiao, respectively; the state health secretary,
Moro Augustine; the health secretary of Varzea Grande, Jaqueline
Guimaraes; and the health surveillance manager for Cuiaba, Vagner
Simplicio, among other municipal secretaries.

[Byline: Antonielle Costa]

