[3] Brazil (Sergipe)
Date: Sun 4 Oct 2009
Source: EmSergipe.com [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://sn1.globo.com/default.asp?act=visualizar&id=112109>


There have been no deaths caused by dengue [virus infection] in 2009
in Aracaju. This is one of the good results achieved by the
intensification of actions in districts where there is greater
occurrence of breeding sites of the mosquito that transmits the
disease [virus]. The positive numbers are a reflection of the constant
visits by health agents to homes, construction sites, and empty lots,
as well as the training of teams and public education campaigns aimed
at prevention and guidance.

Between January and August 2009, in the capital of Sergipe, the number
of notifications of suspected cases of dengue declined by 90 percent
and the number of confirmed cases by 97 percent over the same period
in 2008. According to the coordinator of Epidemiological Surveillance
of the Municipal Health Secretariat (SMS), Taise Cavalcanti, the data
are significant. "There were 1130 suspected cases dengue, with 287
confirmed cases. During the same period in 2008, 11 573 suspected
cases and 10 481 confirmed [cases] were reported," she explained.

According to the latest rapid [household] index survey for _Aedes
aegypti_ (LIRAa), conducted by SMS in early September [2009], of the
39 districts of Aracaju, 23 managed to reduce the house infestation
index (IIP) in relation to the previous survey done in July [2009].
"We found a 24 percent drop in infestation, reaching the level of 2.2
percent, which is considered average risk for the onset of an outbreak
or epidemic of dengue," said Cavalcanti.

The criteria for assessment of the IIP, according to the Ministry of
Health, classifies as 'low' or 'satisfactory' the percentage of
infestation ranging from 0-0.9 percent; as 'average' or 'alert' the
percentage of between 1-3.9, and as 'high' or 'risk of an outbreak'
with rates above 4 percent. "Of all the neighborhoods of the capital,
12 were classified as low risk (satisfactory), 21 classified as medium
risk (alert), and 6 districts as high risk (risk of an outbreak),"
noted the coordinator.

This was the 5th LIRAa conducted by SMS this year [2009]. The
initiative will give priority to areas where the number of foci found
is greatest. "At the beginning of each cycle of mosquito [breeding],
we conduct a LIRAa during the 1st week to make a diagnosis of the
Aracaju districts and to intensify and direct the actions in relation
to the problem encountered at that time," said Cavalcanti.

For her, Santa Maria is a good example of a neighborhood where the
activities of the health agents for endemic diseases have rapidly
increased and shown good results. In the July [2009] survey, the rate
of infestation in the town was 4.2 percent, considered as 'risk of an
outbreak' and is currently at 1.7 percent in the 'medium' risk category.

