[5] Venezuela (Yaracuy)
Date: Sat 3 Oct 2009
Source: El Diario de Yaracuy [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.eldiariodeyaracuy.com/index.php/regionales/comunidad/26866-autoridades-confirman-epidemia-de-dengue>


"For the past 3 weeks we have been committed to dealing with cases of
dengue recorded in the Juan Jose Maya urbanization, where as of 22 Sep
[2009], the 3 [vector control] cycles had been completed." These were
the statements from the director of Environmental Health and Sanitary
Control, Quely Camacho, and the coordinator of Epidemiological
Surveillance and Environmental Health, Ineva Parra, who have confirmed
that a dengue epidemic has been going on for approximately 4-5 weeks.

They claim that they are working in this area and that communities can
attest to that. Up to this past week [week of 1 Oct 2009], the
municipalities most affected by dengue are Sucre, Jose Antonio Paez,
Urachiche, San Felipe, and Cocorote. As for cases that have occurred
in the Juan Jose Maya residential area, they stated that the patients
have been treated and have received support from the community council.

They explained that residents should keep their homes and patios
clean, with no cans, plates, or other objects that serve as water
catchments where [mosquito] larvae may occur, as those most affected
[by dengue virus infections] are children. The idea is [for everyone]
to help the health team. "There must be co-responsibility, and that
municipal councils also identify [places] where a person could be
infected. 90 percent of these activities depend on this partnership,
since home owners must eliminate the breeding sites," they mentioned.

The officials gave details on the work plan they will develop this
month [October 2009]. From yesterday [2 Oct 2009] until Sunday [4 Oct
2009], activities will be carried out in the municipalities of
Independence, Urachiche, and Pena, specifically in the areas at
greatest risk, with 3 [vector control] cycles, until increased
effectiveness is seen and cases disappear, which is why communities
must help implement the extreme [control] measures.

They indicated that fumigation would be done in the Monumento Natural
Maria Lionza, Quibayo, and vicinity, as well as in Parque Leonor
Bernabo, El Buco, and San Felipe El Fuerte around 12 Oct [2009]. They
will also visit educational institutions to give talks and deliver
educational materials. From [Mon 26 Oct 2009] to [Fri 30 Oct] they
will fumigate cemeteries.

They pointed out that mayors' offices should provide support, since
they are responsible to maintain their graveyards clean. They signaled
the importance of calling [health authorities] when a [dengue] case is
suspected.

They mentioned that the government delivered 8 light fumigation units
to reinforce those in use currently, 2 heavier [fumigation] units, and
abate [larvicide].

[Byline: Carolina Cordero]

