[7] Viet Nam
Date: Sun 27 Sep 2009
Source: Saigon Giai Phong (SGGP) Daily [edited]
<http://www.saigon-gpdaily.com.vn/Health/2009/9/74584/>


Dengue fever on the rise
------------------------
By the end of September [2009] Viet Nam has seen more than 58 000
cases of dengue fever, a 25 percent increase compared to the same
period last year [2008], and 44 deaths, recently said the head of the
Health Ministry's Preventive Medicine and Environment Department, Dr
Nguyen Huy Nga.

The numbers of dengue fever cases increased 8-fold in the North and
doubled in the Central and Central Highland regions, Dr Nga said.

Many dengue fever cases were found in areas with poor sanitation and
hygiene, with outbreaks grouped in Ho Chi Minh City and Hanoi.

In Ho Chi Minh City, there were nearly 7000 cases of dengue fever,
double that of the same period last year [2008].

In Hanoi, in the past 9 months, there were more than 6000 cases of
dengue fever, 1/2 of them recorded in August [2009] alone.

Dr Nga said the main reason for the outbreak of dengue fever was that
authorities and citizens have under estimated the effects of dengue
and have failed to act appropriately.

Preventive action faces a number of difficulties due to a surge in the
number of patients in general and the spread of the A (H1N1) flu.
Therefore, many places just focused on preventing A (H1N1) swine flu
and forgot dengue fever, which is dangerous if preventive measures are
not used effectively, Dr Nga adds.

[Byline: Q Lap]

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[Based on the newswire above, more than 58 000 people in Viet Nam have
been infected with dengue virus during January-September 2009, with 44
fatalities. The numbers of dengue cases and deaths have been rapidly
increasing during the past 2 weeks. As of 14 Sep 2009, there were over
44 571 cases and 37 fatalities due to dengue infection (see prior
PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Viet Nam (14) 20090916.3245).

In August 2009, the highest concentration of dengue fever cases moved
northward with Hanoi as Viet Nam's hardest-hit area, after the Mekong
Delta had accounted for 80-90 percent of all cases in 1998-2007.
Nearly 3000 people had dengue over the 1st 8 months in the capital
(see prior PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Viet Nam (15) 20090918.3271).

According to the head of the Health Ministry's Preventive Medicine and
Environment Department, Nguyen Huy Nga, over the past 9 months, there
were more than 6000 cases of dengue fever in Hanoi and nearly 7000
cases in Ho Chi Minh City. The numbers of dengue fever cases increased
8-fold in the North, whereas they increased 2-fold in the South,
comparing to the same period in 2008. As May-October is rainy season
in Viet Nam, it is likely that the number of dengue cases will
continue to rise until the end of October.

For a map of Viet Nam with provinces, see
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VietnameseProvincesMap.png>.
The interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map with direct links to other
outbreaks in Viet Nam and surrounding countries reported on
ProMED-mail and PRO/MBDS can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/r/008c> - Mod.SCM]

